`docs/` is the project's rationale-and-planning layer for the CTX toolchain — no code, but the authoritative source an editor consults before touching architecture, lint policy, or backlog priority. Anything asking "why does this work this way" is answered here, not in code comments.

DECISIONS.md is the load-bearing piece: an append-only ADR log (never renumbered or deleted) that both STATUS.md and DYLINT_RULES.md implicitly depend on for context. STATUS.md's backlog rows cite specific ADR numbers as justification, so if an ADR is superseded (e.g. the ADR-035/036/037/040 pivot from cage-enforced sandboxing to hook-injected sandboxing), any STATUS.md row referencing the old model needs re-evaluation, not just DECISIONS.md. DYLINT_RULES.md doesn't cite ADRs but describes not-yet-built lint rules that partially overlap live enforcement mechanisms in `scripts/` (rationale_check.py, cycle_check.sh) — changes to those scripts or to CHANGES.md format should be checked against this file's rule descriptions for drift.

STATUS.md also references exact file:line locations in the live codebase (e.g. `checks.rs:211`); those go stale independently of ADR content and need separate upkeep. Sort order in STATUS.md (impact desc, difficulty asc) is a convention, not enforced — an editor adding rows must preserve it manually.

No intent.md exists for this directory, so no divergence check applies.